'''Ecological units''', comprise concepts such as [[population]], [[community (ecology)|community]], and - in particular - the [[ecosystem]] as the basic unit<ref>{{cite journal | last=EVANS | first=F. C. | title=Ecosystem as the Basic Unit in Ecology | journal=Science | volume=123 | issue=3208 | date=1956-06-22 | issn=0036-8075 | doi=10.1126/science.123.3208.1127 | pmid=17793430 | pages=1127–1128 | ref=harv}}</ref>, which are at the basis of [[ecological theory]] and research.<ref name="Jax 2006 pp. 237–58">{{cite journal | last=Jax | first=K | title=Ecological units: definitions and application | journal=The Quarterly Review of Biology | volume=81 | issue=3 | year=2006 | issn=0033-5770 | pmid=17051830 | pages=237–58}}</ref> Two common traits can be identified across cultures:<ref>{{cite journal|title=Exploring the Basic Ecological Unit: Ecosystem-Like Concepts in Traditional Societies|author=Fikret Berkes, Mina Kislalioglu, Carl Folke and Madhav Gadgil|journal=Ecosystems|volume=1|issue=5 |year=1998|pages=409–415|url=http://ces.iisc.ernet.in/hpg/envis/mg/pdfs/mg180.pdf}}</ref> # the unit is often defined in terms of a [[geographical boundary]]/[[natural border]] ([[maritime boundary]], [[drainage divide|watershed]]s, etc.) # [[abiotic]] components and [[organism]]s within the unit are considered to be [[biological network|interlinked]]
